in the case of Fraser vs. Major League Soccer (US Court of Appeals, 1st Circuit, No. 01-1296, March 20, 2002). 5. U.S. media ranking is from Gorman (2008). 6. Not all players listed in Table 2 are officially categorized as designated players (DPs). For instance, Bennie Feilhaber of New England Revolution earned a salary in excess of US$350,000 but had a salary cap figure of less than that amount. New England uses allocation money to pay down his salary cap number, so he was not technically a DP. The MLS salary data contain information on all players contracted to MLS, including the base salary earned each year as well as yearly average compensation including signing bonuses, marketing bonuses, and agent fees. For this study, players’ base salaries are used. Team salary structure is based on a team’s roster at the beginning of each season and does not reflect player movement during the season. 7. Players 21 to 30 are considered off-budget players since their salaries do not count toward the cap. These constraints have changed over time, and there are exemptions that make the actual constraint less binding in certain cases. See the MLS website for more details of the 2013 salary rules (http://pressbox.mlssoccer.com/content/rosterrules-and-regulations). 8. Alternative models were also estimated, including linear, log-linear, log-log, and cubic. Results are available upon request. The log-quadratic model is better than the alternative models in terms of R2. The fixed effects are suppressed for brevity, but these results are available from the authors upon request. The constant coefficients reflect the excluded team (Seattle Sounders FC) and the excluded year (2005). 9. See Lawson et al. (2008) for details of Beckham’s injury record in 2007. 10. The marginal effects in Table 5 are calculated using the margins command in STATA Version 12.1 with the option ‘‘atmeans.’’ This command numerically calculates the derivative of the mean expected lnPoint with respect to changing CV, taking the quadratic nature of the function into account. These derivatives are then scaled by mean Points to arrive at an estimate of the first partial of the point production function with respect to CV. The marginal effects presented in Table 6 are constructed in an analogous manner. The margins command also produces confidence intervals for each estimated derivative, all of which are significant at the 5% level or better.

